<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-06-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-06-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="22" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Motley</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 148.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi>
                                </placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-06-13"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 13, 1865.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received and have read with deep
                            interest your despatches from No. 101, of April 30, to No. 106, of the
                            8th ultimo. Your accounts of the feeling with which the news of the
                            assassination of the late President of the United States was received
                            throughout the Austrian empire, as well as elsewhere in Germany, are
                            very gratifying. Your own proceedings upon the case are approved.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">J. Lothrop Motley</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., Vienna.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>